\b Abstract\b0\par
The Digital Certificate Verification System is a console-based Java 17 application that verifies the authenticity of digital certificates issued by educational institutions, companies, and government organizations. The system follows a layered architecture and uses the DAO (Data Access Object) pattern with JDBC and MySQL to store and verify certificates using a unique certificate ID. Administrators log in to the system, manage certificate records, and verify certificates quickly and reliably, reducing fraud and improving trust.\par
\page
\b 1. Introduction\b0\par
In the traditional method of certificate verification, organizations manually inspect physical certificates, signatures, and records. This process is slow, error-prone, and vulnerable to forgery. With the increasing use of digital documents, there is a strong need for a secure and centralized way to verify certificates.\par
The Digital Certificate Verification System provides a digital platform where issued certificates are stored in a central database and can be verified instantly using a unique certificate ID (which can also be encoded into a QR code on the certificate). The application is implemented as a Java console program following the DAO pattern, making it easy to understand, maintain, and extend.\par
\par
\b 2. Objective of the Project\b0\par
- To prevent certificate forgery by maintaining a secure central repository of issued certificates.\par
- To provide fast and reliable verification of certificates using a unique certificate ID.\par
- To allow authorized administrators to register, log in, and manage certificate records.\par
- To demonstrate clean, layered design using the DAO pattern and JDBC.\par
- To serve as a base that can later be extended to a full web-based system.\par
\par
\b 3. Scope of the Project\b0\par
The system supports:\par
- Administrator registration and login.\par
- Adding new certificates with details such as holder name, course, institution, issue date, and expiry date.\par
- Viewing, searching, updating, and deleting certificate records.\par
- Verifying certificates by certificate ID and reporting whether they are VALID, EXPIRED, or NOT VALID.\par
\par
The current version is console-based and does not include a graphical or web user interface, QR code generation/scanning, or advanced role management. These features are possible future enhancements.\par
\par
\b 4. Problem Definition / Statement\b0\par
Manual verification of certificates is time-consuming and vulnerable to forgery. Fake certificates can be produced easily using modern printing and editing tools, and it is difficult for organizations to distinguish genuine certificates from fraudulent ones using only visual inspection. There is a need for a central, tamper-resistant system where every issued certificate can be quickly verified using a unique identifier.\par
\par
\b 5. Feasibility Study\b0\par
\b 5.1 Technical Feasibility\b0\par
- Language: Java 17 (cross-platform, mature, and well supported).\par
- Database: MySQL (open-source, widely used, JDBC support).\par
- Architecture: Layered design (UI, Service, DAO, Model, Utility) with DAO pattern.\par
- Tools: Eclipse IDE, Maven, MySQL Workbench.\par
All required technologies are mature, well-documented, and freely available, so the project is technically feasible.\par
\par
\b 5.2 Economic Feasibility\b0\par
The system uses open-source tools and runs on standard hardware available in most institutions. There are no licensing costs for academic use. Hence, the project is economically feasible.\par
\par
\b 5.3 Operational Feasibility\b0\par
The application is menu-driven and easy to learn. Administrators can quickly perform login, registration, and certificate management tasks using simple numeric choices. Therefore, the system is operationally feasible.\par
\page
\b 6. Existing System\b0\par
In the existing manual system:\par
- Certificates are stored as physical documents.\par
- Verification is done by visually checking signatures and records.\par
- The process is slow, requires physical presence or email exchange, and is hard to audit.\par
- There is a high risk of fake or altered certificates passing as genuine.\par
\par
\b 7. Proposed System\b0\par
The proposed system stores all issued certificates in a MySQL database and allows instant verification using a unique certificate ID. Authorized administrators can log in, add new certificates, update or revoke them, and verify their validity from any machine connected to the database. This reduces fraud, saves time, and improves trust and transparency.\par
\page
