\b 9. System Design\b0\par
\b 9.1 Overall Architecture\b0\par
The system is organized into the following layers and packages:\par
- app: application entry point.\par
- ui: console-based user interface classes.\par
- service: business logic and validation.\par
- dao: DAO interfaces.\par
- dao.jdbc: JDBC implementations of the DAOs.\par
- model: entity classes mapped to database tables.\par
- util: utility classes such as database connection and password hashing.\par
\par
Data flow for verification:\par
- The user interacts with AuthMenu for login/register.\par
- After authentication, the user interacts with ConsoleMenu.\par
- ConsoleMenu calls methods in CertificateService.\par
- CertificateService calls CertificateDao (implemented by CertificateDaoJdbcImpl).\par
- DAO interacts with the MySQL database via DBConnectionUtil.\par
\par
\b 9.2 Module Description\b0\par
- Authentication Module: manages admin registration and login using UserService and UserDao.\par
- Certificate Management Module: handles creation, listing, search, update, and deletion of certificates.\par
- Verification Module: verifies certificate IDs and determines whether they are ACTIVE, EXPIRED, or REVOKED.\par
- Database Utility Module: centralizes DB configuration and connection logic.\par
\par
\b 9.3 Data / Process Flow\b0\par
1. Admin registers with username and password.\par
2. Password is hashed and stored in the users table.\par
3. Admin logs in and, on success, accesses the certificate menu.\par
4. Admin performs CRUD operations on certificates.\par
5. For verification, the system loads the certificate by certificate_id, checks expiry and status, and prints a user-friendly result.\par
