\b 15. Testing\b0\par
Example test cases:\par
- Login with valid credentials: expect success.\par
- Login with invalid password: expect failure.\par
- Register with existing username: expect error.\par
- Add certificate with valid data: expect success and record inserted.\par
- Search certificate by valid and invalid IDs.\par
- Verify certificate with ACTIVE status: expect VALID.\par
- Verify certificate with expired date: expect EXPIRED.\par
\page
\b 16. Security and Encryption Approach\b0\par
- Passwords are stored as SHA-256 hashes using PasswordUtil.\par
- Only authenticated administrators can access certificate operations.\par
- Database access is restricted via MySQL user credentials defined in db.properties.\par
- Future improvements can include SSL connections and field-level encryption.\par
\par
\b 17. Limitations\b0\par
- Console-based UI only.\par
- Single admin role; no fine-grained authorization.\par
- No QR code generation or scanning integration.\par
\par
\b 18. Future Enhancements\b0\par
- Web-based interface (REST API and web frontend).\par
- QR code generation and scanning for certificate IDs.\par
- Role-based access control (Admin, Verifier, Viewer).\par
- Email or SMS notifications.\par
\par
\b 19. Conclusion\b0\par
The Digital Certificate Verification System demonstrates a secure, layered, and maintainable approach to certificate verification. By replacing manual checks with a database-driven solution, the system improves speed, accuracy, and trust, and provides a strong foundation for further enhancements.\par
